<article id="ocpArticleContent" class="ocpArticleContent">
        <h1>Set up email in Outlook 2010 or Outlook 2013 for Office 365 or Exchange-based accounts</h1>
        <section class="ocpSummary">
          <p>Learn how to get Outlook 2013 or Outlook 2010 set up to work with Office 365 or Microsoft Exchange-based email accounts.</p>
        </section>
        <a name="__top">	</a>
        <section class="ocpIntroduction">
          <p>You can set up your Office 365 for business or other Microsoft Exchange-based email with Outlook 2010 or Outlook 2013. You can do this in the setup wizard by simply typing your email address and password. Outlook uses a process called Autodiscover to automatically find your settings and to set up an Exchange connection to your account. If you aren’t connecting to an Office 365 or other Exchange-based account (for example, a Gmail or Yahoo! account), see <a href="#__what_else_do" class="ocpInlineLink" title="What else do I need to know?">What else do I need to know?</a></p>
          <p>If you’re an Office 365 user using Outlook 2010, you need to set up your desktop before you can set up Outlook to access your account. For more information, see <a href="Use-my-current-Office-desktop-apps-with-Office-365-3324b8b8-dceb-45e2-ac24-c642720108f7" class="ocpArticleLink" title="Use my current Office desktop apps with Office 365">Use my current Office desktop apps with Office 365</a>. For information about how to set up email in Outlook 2007, see <a href="Set-up-email-in-Outlook-2007-1cf5c44a-43c1-4332-bb54-0d7545322cc0" class="ocpArticleLink" title="Set up email in Outlook 2007">Set up email in Outlook 2007</a>. </p>
          <p>
            <b class="ocpNote"> Note </b>  You may be able to manually set up Outlook 2010 or Outlook 2013 to access your email account by using Post Office Protocol (POP) or Internet Message Access Protocol (IMAP). Using Autodiscover is suggested, however, because the process automatically sets up an Exchange connection to your account. With POP or IMAP, you can't use many of the calendar and other collaboration features that are available when you connect to your account by using Exchange. For more information, see <a href="#__what_else_do" class="ocpInlineLink" title="What else do I need to know?">What else do I need to know?</a></p>
        </section>
        <section class="ocpSection">
          <h2>In this article</h2>
          <a name="___toc___1_l">	</a>
          <dl class="ocpTOC">
            <dd>
              <p>
                <a href="#__toc332372186" class="ocpInlineLink" title="Set up an Exchange connection to your email in Outlook 2010 or Outlook 2013">Set up an Exchange connection to your email in Outlook 2010 or Outlook 2013</a>
              </p>
            </dd>
            <dd>
              <p>
                <a href="#__toc332372187" class="ocpInlineLink" title="Set up a POP3 or IMAP4 connection to your email in Outlook 2010 or Outlook 2013">Set up a POP3 or IMAP4 connection to your email in Outlook 2010 or Outlook 2013</a>
              </p>
              <dl>
                <dd>
                  <p>
                    <a href="#__find_your_pop" class="ocpInlineLink" title="Find your POP or IMAP server settings">Find your POP or IMAP server settings</a>
                  </p>
                </dd>
              </dl>
            </dd>
            <dd>
              <p>
                <a href="#__what_else_do" class="ocpInlineLink" title="What else do I need to know?">What else do I need to know?</a>
              </p>
            </dd>
